@TnTOmnibus - But you stated specifically that the manner in which it was input is important. You said that alternating rather than direct current is what causes the generation of heat with respect to the movement of ions. I’m not basing my statement on some advanced knowledge of this principle OR a belief. I merely interpreted what you said and applied the additional principles stipulated in the patent.

If it is this back and forth movement of ions which created the heat, wouldn’t the heat be greater at a higher rate of frequency - a multiplier effect? Wouldn’t the heat be lower if you dropped the cycles from 50Hz to 2Hz? 

I’m just saying that it seems worthy of exploring rather than making assumptions. Prove me / them wrong. Obviously the patent office seemed to find it valid. A man with integrity would conduct that experiment after making such a statement - right? 🤷🏻‍♂️
